The problem is the setting is really a tri-state switch of "disabled", "warning", "enabled". SELinux setup on RHEL works the same (disabled, permissive, where it logs but don't block access, and enabled where it blocks access). And the reason I kept existing setting is for backward compatibility, so users don't have to re-write or port their config files.

Something like `reduce_limit_debug = true | false` needs an explanation how it interacts with `reduce_limit`. For example reduce `reduce_limit_debug` would only work with `reduce_limit = false`, which is not intuitive. When `reduce_limit = true` there is not much need to log as it already blows up and user will find out.

